## Database Optimization Complete ✅

**Problem:** The `orders` table has **500 million rows** but only a primary key index on `id`. Every order-related query (by user, by status, by date) was doing a full sequential scan — brutal at that scale.

**What I did:** Created 3 new B-Tree indexes using `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY` (the safe, non-blocking method):

| Index | Column | Helps with |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | "Show me my orders" — user order history lookups |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Filtering by pending/shipped/completed etc. |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Date-range queries, recent orders, reporting |

**Zero disruption:** All indexes were built with `CONCURRENTLY`, which only acquires a `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` — writes (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) continued uninterrupted throughout. Lock check confirms no conflicts remain.

**Expected impact:** Queries that previously scanned all 500M rows should now hit the index and return in milliseconds instead of seconds/minutes. The improvement will be most dramatic for user-facing "my orders" pages and any status-filtered views.
